   "source": [
    "> Copyright (c) 2022 Massachusetts Institute of Technology  \n",
    "> SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generating Adversarial Perturbations\n",
    "\n",
    "Solving for adversarial perturbations is a common task in Robust AI. An adversarial perturbation for a given input, $x$, with corresponding label, $y$, can be computed by solving the following optimization objective:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\max_{||\\delta||_p<\\epsilon} \\mathcal{L}\\left(f_\\theta(x+\\delta), y\\right) $$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\delta$ is the perturbation, $f_\\theta$ is a machine learning model parameterized by $\\theta$, $\\mathcal{L}$ is the loss function (e.g., cross-entropy), $||\\delta||_p$ is the $L^p$-norm of the perturbation (for this example we'll be using $p=2$), and $\\epsilon$ is the maximum allowable size of the perturbation.\n",
    "\n",
    "This tutorial demonstrates how to use [rai_toolbox.perturbations.gradient_ascent](https://mit-ll-responsible-ai.github.io/responsible-ai-toolbox/generated/rai_toolbox.perturbations.gradient_ascent.html#rai_toolbox.perturbations.gradient_ascent) to generate $L^2$-norm-constrained adversarial perturbations using projected gradient descent (PGD) for images from the [CIFAR-10](https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html) dataset, based on both a standard classification model and a robust (i.e., adversarially-trained) model. \n",
    "We then compute adversarial accuracy for a few batches of samples from the test set, and use this to generate robustness curves for increasing values of perturbation size, $\\epsilon$.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "## Boilerplate setup\n",
    "In the notebook, we will start by importing modules from the toolbox and 3rd party libraries needed for this tutorial. Then we will specify directories where data and models will be stored,  and determine if computations will be run on CPU or GPU (depending on the resources available on your machine)."

    "from functools import partial\n",
    "from pathlib import Path\n",

    "import torch\n",
    "import torchvision\n",
    "\n",
    "from rai_toolbox.mushin import load_from_checkpoint\n",
    "from rai_toolbox.perturbations import gradient_ascent, AdditivePerturbation\n",
    "from rai_toolbox.optim import L2ProjectedOptim\n",
    "\n",
    "from rai_experiments.models.small_resnet import resnet50"
   ]
  },

    "We will also define a function for plotting images:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_images(x, y, class_names, x_adv=None, y_adv=None):\n",
    "    if x_adv is not None:\n",
    "        fig, ax = plt.subplots(3,10,figsize=(20,5))\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,10,figsize=(20,5))\n",
    "\n",
    "    for i in range(10):\n",
    "        if x_adv is not None:\n",
    "            ax[0,i].imshow(x[i].permute(1,2,0))\n",
    "            ax[0,i].set_title(class_names[y[i]])\n",
    "            ax[0,i].axis(\"off\")\n",
    "            ax[1,i].imshow(x_adv[i].detach().cpu().permute(1,2,0))\n",
    "            if y_adv[i].item()!=y[i].item():\n",
    "                ax[1,i].set_title(class_names[y_adv[i]],color='r')\n",
    "            else:\n",
    "                ax[1,i].set_title(class_names[y_adv[i]],color='k')\n",
    "            ax[1,i].axis(\"off\")\n",
    "            ax[2,i].imshow((torch.abs(x[i]-x_adv[i].detach().cpu())*25).clamp_(0, 1).permute(1,2,0))\n",
    "            ax[2,i].axis(\"off\")\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            ax[i].imshow(x[i].permute(1,2,0))\n",
    "            ax[i].set_title(class_names[y[i]])\n",
    "            ax[i].axis(\"off\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Loading the CIFAR-10 dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "CIFAR-10 is a dataset containing 32x32 RGB images; each image depicts an object or animal belonging to one of ten classes. Here we will load images from the test set and plot a few example images from each class."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Files already downloaded and verified\n",
      "Number of Test Samples: 10000\n",
      "Classes: ['airplane', 'automobile', 'bird', 'cat', 'deer', 'dog', 'frog', 'horse', 'ship', 'truck']\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "BATCH_SIZE = 10\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load CIFAR10 test dataset\n",
    "dataset = torchvision.datasets.CIFAR10(\n",
    "    root=DATA_DIR,\n",
    "    train=False,\n",
    "    download=True,\n",
    "    transform=torchvision.transforms.ToTensor(),\n",
    ")\n",
    "print(f\"Number of Test Samples: {len(dataset)}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Grab class names\n",
    "class_names = dataset.classes\n",
    "print(f\"Classes: {class_names}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Instantiate a data loader\n",
    "dataloader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(\n",
    "    dataset,\n",
    "    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,\n",
    "    shuffle=False,\n",
    "    drop_last=True,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,

     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Sample first batch of test data and plot\n",
    "x, y = next(iter(dataloader))\n",
    "plot_images(x, y, class_names)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Loading pre-trained CIFAR-10 models\n",
    "\n",
    "Next we will load two pre-trained models. First, `model_robust`, is a classification model that was trained against adversarially-generated training data. Second, `model_standard`, is a classification model that was trained against CIFAR-10 using standard (i.e., non-adversarial) data augmentation procedures. The weights for both models are derived from Madrylab's [robustness](https://github.com/MadryLab/robustness) library:\n",
    "\n",
    "- `mitll_cifar_l2_1_0.pt`: A simplified data structure of the pre-trained model available via the [README](https://github.com/MadryLab/robustness/blob/master/README.rst). This is a ResNet-50 model trained with perturbations generated via PGD using perturbations constrained to $L^2$-ball of radius $\\epsilon=1.0$\n",
    "- `mitll_cifar_nat.pt`: A simplified data structure of the pre-trained model available via the [README](https://github.com/MadryLab/robustness/blob/master/README.rst). This is a ResNet-50 model trained using standard training with no adversarial perturbations in the loop (i.e., $\\epsilon=0$)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Function for loading model from checkpoint path\n",
    "# and adding a pre-processing module to normalize\n",
    "# the data by its mean and standard deviation\n",
    "def load_model(ckpt):\n",
    "    base_model = load_from_checkpoint(\n",
    "        model = resnet50(),\n",
    "        ckpt = ckpt,\n",
    "        weights_key=\"state_dict\",\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    # Transform to normalize the data samples by the mean and standard deviation\n",
    "    normalizer = torchvision.transforms.transforms.Normalize(\n",
    "        mean=[0.4914, 0.4822, 0.4465],\n",
    "        std=[0.2023, 0.1994, 0.2010],\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    model = torch.nn.Sequential(normalizer, base_model)\n",
    "    return model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Load pre-trained model that was trained using a robust approach (i.e., adversarial training)\n",
    "ckpt_robust = \"mitll_cifar_l2_1_0.pt\"\n",
    "model_robust = load_model(ckpt_robust)\n",
    "model_robust.eval();\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load pre-trained model that was trained with standard approach\n",
    "ckpt_standard = \"mitll_cifar_nat.pt\"\n",
    "model_standard = load_model(ckpt_standard)\n",
    "model_standard.eval();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Obtaining adversarial perturbations for a batch of data\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we will use the [gradient_ascent](https://mit-ll-responsible-ai.github.io/responsible-ai-toolbox/generated/rai_toolbox.perturbations.gradient_ascent.html) function with an [AdditivePerturbation](https://mit-ll-responsible-ai.github.io/responsible-ai-toolbox/generated/rai_toolbox.perturbations.AdditivePerturbation.html) model and [L2ProjectedOptim](https://mit-ll-responsible-ai.github.io/responsible-ai-toolbox/generated/rai_toolbox.optim.L2ProjectedOptim.html) optimizer from the toolbox to solve for $L^2$-norm-constrained adversarial perturbations to samples from the dataset. These are perturbations that maximize  within the given constraints  the cross-entropy classification loss measured on our model's predictions.\n",
    "\n",
    "`AdditivePerturbation` implements $x_{adv}=x+\\delta$, where $\\delta$ is the sole trainable parameter of the perturbation model.\n",
    "\n",
    "We will use `functools.partial` to set default values for `gradient_ascent`, so that they can be used consistently across our two models."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Define perturbation model\n",
    "perturbation_model = AdditivePerturbation(x.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define parameters for perturbation optimizer\n",
    "EPS = 0.5  # L2-norm of perturbation\n",
    "STEPS = 10  # number of gradient steps during perturbation optimization\n",
    "FACTOR = 2.5  # factor for determining step size (learning rate)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Function for selecting step size (learning rate) for perturbation optimizer\n",
    "def get_stepsize(factor: float, steps: int, epsilon: float) -> float:\n",
    "    return factor * epsilon / steps\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define perturbation solver that we will apply to multiple models.\n",
    "# Fills out all params for `gradient_ascent` except `data`, `target`, and `model`.\n",
    "# Signature: solver(data: Tensor, target: Tensor, model: nn.Module)\n",
    "solver = partial(\n",
    "    gradient_ascent,\n",
    "    perturbation_model = perturbation_model.to(device),\n",
    "    optimizer=L2ProjectedOptim,\n",
    "    lr=get_stepsize(FACTOR, STEPS, EPS),\n",
    "    epsilon=EPS,\n",
    "    steps=STEPS,\n",
    "    targeted=False,\n",
    "    use_best=True,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We will first solve for a single batch of adversarial perturbations for our standard model.\n",
    "Given a batch of images, this will produce a corresponding batch of perturbed images and we will plot each image, perturbed image, and the corresponding perturbation that we solved for, which attempts to \"fool\" the standard model.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x360 with 30 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Solve for adversarial perturbations to standard model and plot\n",
    "x_adv, loss_adv = solver(\n",
    "    data=x.to(device),\n",
    "    target=y.to(device),\n",
    "    model=model_standard.to(device)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compute predictions for adversarial samples\n",
    "x_adv = x_adv.clamp_(0, 1)\n",
    "logits_adv = model_standard(x_adv)\n",
    "y_adv = torch.argmax(logits_adv, axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot original and adversarial samples\n",
    "plot_images(x, y, class_names, x_adv, y_adv)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The top row is the original image with true label, the second row is the adversarially-perturbed image with the label predicted by the model, and the third row is the perturbation (multiplied by $25$ so it can be viewed more easily).\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we now use the same batch of data to produce adversarial examples for our robust model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x360 with 30 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Repeat for robust model\n",
    "x_adv, loss_adv = solver(\n",
    "    data=x.to(device),\n",
    "    target=y.to(device),\n",
    "    model=model_robust.to(device)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compute predictions for adversarial samples\n",
    "x_adv = x_adv.clamp_(0, 1)\n",
    "logits_adv = model_robust(x_adv)\n",
    "y_adv = torch.argmax(logits_adv, axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot original and adversarial samples\n",
    "plot_images(x, y, class_names, x_adv, y_adv)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that the robust model is making fewer mistakes on the adversarially-perturbed images, and its perturbations also appear to contain more structure."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Computing adversarial accuracy over multiple batches\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, we'll compute adversarial accuracy (i.e., accuracy of the model on adversarially-perturbed images) across multiple batches of validation data, and for increasing values of perturbation size, $\\epsilon$, to generate robustness curves and visualize how quickly performance drops off for each of the models.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we define our own function for iterating over batches and computing accuracy, but note that this can easily been integrated with [PyTorch Lightning's](https://www.pytorchlightning.ai/) framework to save us from writing such boilerplate code."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Define function for computing adversarial perturbations and adversarial accuracy over multiple batches\n",
    "def compute_adversarial_accuracy(model, dataloader, epsilons, num_batches, device):\n",
    "    accuracies = []\n",
    "\n",
    "    model = model.to(device)\n",
    "    for EPS in epsilons:\n",
    "        print(f\"Epsilon = {EPS}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "        # solver(data: Tensor, target: Tensor) \n",
    "        solver = partial(\n",
    "            gradient_ascent,\n",
    "            model=model,\n",
    "            optimizer=L2ProjectedOptim,\n",
    "            lr=get_stepsize(FACTOR, STEPS, EPS),\n",
    "            epsilon=EPS,\n",
    "            steps=STEPS,\n",
    "            targeted=False,\n",
    "            use_best=True,\n",
    "        )\n",
    "\n",
    "        data_iter = iter(dataloader)\n",
    "        accur = 0.0\n",
    "        for i in tqdm(range(num_batches)):\n",
    "            # Sample next batch\n",
    "            x, y = next(data_iter)\n",
    "\n",
    "            # Solve for perturbation\n",
    "            x_adv, _ = solver(data=x.to(device), target=y.to(device))\n",
    "\n",
    "            # Compute accuracy\n",
    "            x_adv = x_adv.clamp_(0, 1)\n",
    "            logits_adv = model(x_adv)\n",
    "            y_adv = torch.argmax(logits_adv, axis=1).detach().cpu()\n",
    "            accur += sum(y == y_adv) / len(x)\n",
    "\n",
    "        accuracies.append(accur / num_batches)\n",
    "    return accuracies"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Compute adversarial accuracy for both models using 10 batches of data and multiple values of epsilon"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Compute adversarial accuracy of both models for multiple values of epsilon\n",
    "num_batches = 10\n",
    "epsilons = [0, 0.25, 0.5, 1, 2]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,

    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Compute adversarial accuracy for standard model\n",
    "accuracies_standard = compute_adversarial_accuracy(\n",
    "    model_standard,\n",
    "    dataloader,\n",
    "    epsilons,\n",
    "    num_batches,\n",
    "    device=device,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },

   "execution_count": 15,

     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Epsilon = 0.5\n"
     ]

   "source": [
    "While the standard model is the most accurate on unperturbed data ($\\epsilon=0$), it is reduced to near-guessing performance by the smallest-magnitude adversarial perturbations. By contrast, the robust model's performance decays much more gradually in light of perturbations of increasing strength.\n",
